[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:testify-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] In computer programming, a **mock object** is an object that imitates a production object in limited ways.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] A programmer might use a mock object as a test double for software testing.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] A mock object can also be used in generic programming.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] A mock object can be useful to the software tester like a car designer uses a crash test dummy to simulate a human in a vehicle impact.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] In a unit test, mock objects can simulate the behavior of complex, real objects and are therefore useful when a real object is impractical or impossible to incorporate into a unit test.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] For example, an alarm clock program which causes a bell to ring at a certain time might get the current time from a time service.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] To test this, the test must wait until the alarm time to know whether it has rung the bell correctly.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] If a mock time service is used in place of the real time service, it can be programmed to provide the bell-ringing time (or any other time) regardless of the real time, so that the alarm clock program can be tested in isolation.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Mock objects have the same interface as the real objects they mimic, allowing a client object to remain unaware of whether it is using a real object or a mock object.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Many available mock object frameworks allow the programmer to specify which methods will be invoked on a mock object, in what order, what parameters will be passed to them, and what values will be returned.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Thus, the behavior of a complex object such as a network socket can be mimicked by a mock object, allowing the programmer to discover whether the object being tested responds appropriately to the wide variety of states such mock objects may be in.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] The definitions of mock, fake and stub are not consistent across the literature.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Nonetheless, all represent a production object in a testing environment by exposing the same interface.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Regardless of name, the simplest form returns pre-arranged responses (as in a method stub) and the most complex form imitates a production object's complete logic.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Such a test object might contain assertions to examine the context of each call.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] For example, a mock object might assert the order in which its methods are called, or assert consistency of data across method calls.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] In the book *The Art of Unit Testing* mocks are described as a fake object that helps decide whether a test failed or passed by verifying whether an interaction with an object occurred.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] In that book, *fakes* are anything that is not real, which, based on their usage, can be either *stubs* or *mocks*.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Consider an example where an authorization subsystem has been mocked.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] The mock object implements an `isUserAllowed(task : Task) : boolean` method to match that in the real authorization class.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Many advantages follow if it also exposes an `isAllowed : boolean` property, which is not present in the real class.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] This allows test code to easily set the expectation that a user will, or will not, be granted permission in the next call and therefore to readily test the behavior of the rest of the system in either case.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Similarly, mock-only settings could ensure that subsequent calls to the sub-system will cause it to throw an exception, hang without responding, or return `null` etc.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Thus, it is possible to develop and test client behaviors for realistic fault conditions in back-end sub-systems, as well as for their expected responses.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Without such a simple and flexible mock system, testing each of these situations may be too laborious for them to be given proper consideration.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] A mock database object's `save(person : Person)` method may not contain much (if any) implementation code.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] It might check the existence and perhaps the validity of the Person object passed in for saving (see fake vs. mock discussion above), but beyond that there might be no other implementation.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] The mock method could add an entry to a public log string.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] The entry need be no more than "Person saved", or it may include some details from the person object instance, such as a name or ID.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] If the test code also checks the final contents of the log string after various series of operations involving the mock database, then it is possible to verify that in each case exactly the expected number of database saves have been performed.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] This can find otherwise invisible performance-sapping bugs, for example, where a developer, nervous of losing data, has coded repeated calls to `save()` where just one would have sufficed.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Programmers working with the test-driven development (TDD) method make use of mock objects when writing software.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Mock objects meet the interface requirements of, and stand in for, more complex real ones; thus they allow programmers to write and unit-test functionality in one area without calling complex underlying or collaborating classes.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Using mock objects allows developers to focus their tests on the behavior of the system under test without worrying about its dependencies.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] For example, testing a complex algorithm based on multiple objects being in particular states can be clearly expressed using mock objects in place of real objects.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Apart from complexity issues and the benefits gained from this separation of concerns, there are practical speed issues involved.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Developing a realistic piece of software using TDD may easily involve several hundred unit tests.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] If many of these induce communication with databases, web services and other out-of-process or networked systems, then the suite of unit tests will quickly become too slow to be run regularly.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] This in turn leads to bad habits and a reluctance by the developer to maintain the basic tenets of TDD.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] When mock objects are replaced by real ones, the end-to-end functionality will need further testing.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] These will be integration tests rather than unit tests.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] The use of mock objects can closely couple the unit tests to the implementation of the code that is being tested.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] This illustrates that unit tests should test a method's external behavior rather than its internal implementation.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Over-use of mock objects as part of a suite of unit tests can result in a dramatic increase in the amount of maintenance that needs to be performed on the tests themselves during system evolution as refactoring takes place.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] The improper maintenance of such tests during evolution could allow bugs to be missed that would otherwise be caught by unit tests that use instances of real classes.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Conversely, simply mocking one method might require far less configuration than setting up an entire real class and therefore reduce maintenance needs.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] Mock objects have to accurately model the behavior of the object they are mocking, which can be difficult to achieve if the object being mocked comes from another developer or project or if it has not even been written yet.
[src:testify-go/mock-object] If the behavior is not modelled correctly, then the unit tests may register a pass even though a failure would occur at run time under the same conditions that the unit test is exercising, thus rendering the unit test inaccurate.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:testify-go/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Alternative approaches to writing automated tests is to write all of the production code before starting on the test code or to write all of the test code before starting on the production code.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] With TDD, both are written together, therefore shortening debugging time necessities.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] TDD is related to the test-first programming concepts of extreme programming, begun in 1999, but more recently has created more general interest in its own right.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Programmers also apply the concept to improving and debugging legacy code developed with older techniques.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Software engineer Kent Beck, who is credited with having developed or "rediscovered" the technique, stated in 2003 that TDD encourages simple designs and inspires confidence.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] — Kent Beck, "Why does Kent Beck refer to the 'rediscovery' of test-driven development?
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] The TDD steps vary somewhat by author in count and description, but are generally as follows.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] These are based on the book *Test-Driven Development by Example*, and Kent Beck's Canon TDD article.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] List the expected variants in the new behavior.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] pass if the variant in the new behavior is met.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This shows that new code is actually needed for the desired feature.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] It rules out the possibility that the new test is flawed and will always pass.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] No code should be added beyond the tested functionality.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] If any fail, fix failing tests with minimal changes until all pass.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] In particular, hard-coded test data should be removed from the production code.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Running the test suite after each refactor ensures that no existing functionality is broken.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Repeat the process, starting at step 2, with each test on the list until all tests are implemented and passing.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Each tests should be small and commits made often.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] If new code fails some tests, the programmer can undo or revert rather than debug excessively.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] When using external libraries, it is important not to write tests that are so small as to effectively test merely the library itself, unless there is some reason to believe that the library is buggy or not feature-rich enough to serve all the needs of the software under development.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] TDD has been adopted outside of software development, in both product and service teams, as **test-driven work**.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] For testing to be successful, it needs to be practiced at the micro and macro levels.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Every method in a class, every input data value, log message, and error code, amongst other data points, need to be tested.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Similar to TDD, non-software teams develop quality control (QC) checks (usually manual tests rather than automated tests) for each aspect of the work prior to commencing.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] These QC checks are then used to inform the design and validate the associated outcomes.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] There are various aspects to using test-driven development, for example the principles of "keep it simple, stupid" (KISS) and "You aren't gonna need it" (YAGNI).
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] By focusing on writing only the code necessary to pass tests, designs can often be cleaner and clearer than is achieved by other methods.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] In *Test-Driven Development by Example*, Kent Beck also suggests the principle "Fake it till you make it".
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] To achieve some advanced design concept such as a design pattern, tests are written that generate that design.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] The code may remain simpler than the target pattern, but still pass all required tests.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This can be unsettling at first but it allows the developer to focus only on what is important.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Writing the tests first: The tests should be written before the functionality that is to be tested.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This has been claimed to have many benefits.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] It helps ensure that the application is written for testability, as the developers must consider how to test the application from the outset rather than adding it later.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] It also ensures that tests for every feature gets written.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Additionally, writing the tests first leads to a deeper and earlier understanding of the product requirements, ensures the effectiveness of the test code, and maintains a continual focus on software quality.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] When writing feature-first code, there is a tendency by developers and organizations to push the developer on to the next feature, even neglecting testing entirely.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] The first TDD test might not even compile at first, because the classes and methods it requires may not yet exist.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Nevertheless, that first test functions as the beginning of an executable specification.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Each test case fails initially: This ensures that the test really works and can catch an error.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Once this is shown, the underlying functionality can be implemented.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This has led to the "test-driven development mantra", which is "red/green/refactor", where red means *fail* and green means *pass*.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Test-driven development constantly repeats the steps of adding test cases that fail, passing them, and refactoring.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Receiving the expected test results at each stage reinforces the developer's mental model of the code, boosts confidence and increases productivity.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] In test-driven development, writing tests before implementation raises questions about testing private methods versus testing only through public interfaces.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This choice affects the design of both test code and production code.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Test-driven development relies primarily on unit tests for its rapid red-green-refactor cycle.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] These tests execute quickly by avoiding process boundaries, network connections, or external dependencies.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] While TDD practitioners also write integration tests to verify component interactions, these slower tests are kept separate from the more frequent unit test runs.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Testing multiple integrated modules together also makes it more difficult to identify the source of failures.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] When code under development relies on external dependencies, TDD encourages the use of test doubles to maintain fast, isolated unit tests.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] The typical approach involves using interfaces to separate external dependencies and implementing test doubles for testing purposes.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Since test doubles don't prove the connection to real external components, TDD practitioners supplement unit tests with integration testing at appropriate levels.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] To keep execution faster and more reliable, testing is maximized at the unit level while minimizing slower tests at higher levels.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] For TDD, a unit is most commonly defined as a class, or a group of related functions often called a module.
