[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Empirical studies of test-driven development (TDD) have reported mixed results.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Reviews generally find evidence that TDD can improve some measures of software quality, but its effect on productivity is less consistent.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] A 2013 meta-analysis of 27 studies found a small positive effect on external quality and little or no overall effect on productivity, with larger quality gains but also larger productivity reductions in industrial studies.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] A 2016 systematic review of studies published between 1999 and 2014 found that most studies reported improvements in internal and external software quality, but that productivity results varied between academic and industrial settings.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] A comparative analysis of empirical studies concluded that TDD may reduce introduced defects and lead to more maintainable code, while some implemented code may be smaller or less complex.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] However, an industry experiment with professional developers found that the effect of TDD depended strongly on task characteristics, and concluded that further evidence was needed before determining whether TDD was better or worse than incremental test-last development in industrial settings.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] A later study of TDD process characteristics found that quality and productivity improvements were associated more with small, uniform development steps than with the test-first ordering itself.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] TDD can provide rapid feedback during development because the developer repeatedly runs a growing set of automated tests.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This can make regressions easier to detect soon after they are introduced, and can support refactoring by providing a safety net for behavioral changes.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Because tests are written before the corresponding production code, the developer must consider the desired behavior and interface of the code before implementation.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] This can encourage smaller units of code, looser coupling, and clearer interfaces, especially when tests are written against public behavior rather than implementation details.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] TDD also tends to produce a suite of automated tests as a by-product of development.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Such tests can be useful in continuous integration workflows, where changes are tested frequently before being merged or released.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] In this sense, TDD may improve confidence in later changes, although passing unit tests do not by themselves prove that the software is correct.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] TDD is not a substitute for other forms of software testing.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Since TDD is commonly practiced through unit testing, it may not adequately test behavior that depends on user interfaces, databases, distributed systems, hardware, timing, security properties, or interactions between components.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] These areas often require additional integration testing, system testing, acceptance testing, usability testing, or other specialized testing methods.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Tests written during TDD may share the same misunderstandings as the production code.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] If a developer misinterprets a requirement, both the test and the implementation can encode the same incorrect assumption, causing the test to pass while the software remains wrong.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] A large number of passing tests can therefore create a false sense of security if the tests are incomplete, overly narrow, or focused on implementation details rather than externally visible behavior.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Automated tests also create maintenance costs.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] Tests that are tightly coupled to internal implementation details, use excessive mocking, rely on fragile timing assumptions, or contain duplicated setup code can become difficult to maintain.
[src:testify-go/test-driven-development] In some contexts, especially complex brownfield tasks or projects with limited automated-testing experience, the time required to write and maintain tests may reduce short-term productivity.
