[src:testify-go/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:testify-go/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
